WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.347 --> 00:00:01.930
MALE SPEAKER: I'm
pleased to introduce

00:00:01.930 --> 00:00:04.560
Jenny Lawson, otherwise
known as The Bloggess.

00:00:04.560 --> 00:00:07.010
Jenny's former book, "Let's
Pretend This Never Happened,"

00:00:07.010 --> 00:00:09.420
was a number one New
York Times Bestseller.

00:00:09.420 --> 00:00:11.310
And her current book,
"Furiously Happy,"

00:00:11.310 --> 00:00:14.770
has already been named one of
the best humor books of 2015

00:00:14.770 --> 00:00:15.870
by Amazon.

00:00:15.870 --> 00:00:19.710
I have to admit, being up
here in front of all of you

00:00:19.710 --> 00:00:21.490
makes me a little bit anxious.

00:00:21.490 --> 00:00:24.034
But it will lessen shortly.

00:00:24.034 --> 00:00:25.700
However, there's
another type of anxiety

00:00:25.700 --> 00:00:27.650
that only increases over time.

00:00:27.650 --> 00:00:30.630
It may be crippling or
lead to other dark places.

00:00:30.630 --> 00:00:32.890
Jenny's visited those
places, and she's

00:00:32.890 --> 00:00:35.160
determined to live the
rest of her life a bit

00:00:35.160 --> 00:00:37.120
more happy because of them.

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:39.390
And she's written
that in her book.

00:00:39.390 --> 00:00:43.390
It's a journey full of fun,
unexpected, and sometimes

00:00:43.390 --> 00:00:45.042
serious events.

00:00:45.042 --> 00:00:46.500
If you're like me
after reading it,

00:00:46.500 --> 00:00:48.540
you may want to tell
your friends about it.

00:00:48.540 --> 00:00:51.630
On the other hand,
as Jenny says,

00:00:51.630 --> 00:00:54.240
if you don't like the
book, then maybe you're

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:56.450
just not crazy
enough to enjoy it.

00:00:56.450 --> 00:00:58.700
Either way, you win.

00:00:58.700 --> 00:01:01.376
Please join me in giving a
warm welcome to Jenny Lawson.

00:01:01.376 --> 00:01:04.154
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:10.130 --> 00:01:14.020
JENNY LAWSON: So first
of all, I'm gonna curse.

00:01:14.020 --> 00:01:16.502
So I'm going to tell
you that right now.

00:01:16.502 --> 00:01:18.950
So just be prepared.

00:01:18.950 --> 00:01:22.630
Secondly, usually
I spend my lunch

00:01:22.630 --> 00:01:25.732
having Google entertain me,
so this is fucking weird.

00:01:25.732 --> 00:01:26.706
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:26.706 --> 00:01:28.580
JENNY LAWSON: This is
like weird opposite day

00:01:28.580 --> 00:01:30.308
and it's freaking me out.

00:01:30.308 --> 00:01:36.790
Also, when I told my husband
that I was going to be here,

00:01:36.790 --> 00:01:40.520
he said, oh, you should check
out the driverless cars.

00:01:40.520 --> 00:01:43.020
And I was like, I don't even
know what you're talking about.

00:01:43.020 --> 00:01:44.800
He was like, oh these
driverless cars.

00:01:44.800 --> 00:01:47.080
And I was just like,
that's a terrible idea.

00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:48.764
So I'm just telling
you right now.

00:01:48.764 --> 00:01:50.830
I think maybe y'all
aren't in control of that.

00:01:50.830 --> 00:01:56.510
So good job, because driverless
cars, I had one of those,

00:01:56.510 --> 00:01:58.775
and it hit people.

00:01:58.775 --> 00:02:01.770
If you don't put it completely
in park, it's not good.

00:02:01.770 --> 00:02:04.220
You can get tickets.

00:02:04.220 --> 00:02:07.509
And also I thought it would
be really strange to have

00:02:07.509 --> 00:02:09.425
a driverless car-- and
you have to forgive me,

00:02:09.425 --> 00:02:12.200
because I absolutely know
nothing about them except

00:02:12.200 --> 00:02:15.190
the word "driverless
car"-- words--

00:02:15.190 --> 00:02:19.610
but I hate to drive because
it makes me very anxious,

00:02:19.610 --> 00:02:21.410
and so my husband
always drives me.

00:02:21.410 --> 00:02:25.820
And I think it would be really
uncomfortable driving in a car

00:02:25.820 --> 00:02:28.395
where there wasn't a
driver constantly cursing

00:02:28.395 --> 00:02:31.770
at everyone else, because
that's how I know that I

00:02:31.770 --> 00:02:33.160
someone's taking care of me.

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:37.749
And also when he's
always driving,

00:02:37.749 --> 00:02:40.040
and he's like, well, where
do you want to go eat lunch?

00:02:40.040 --> 00:02:41.873
And I'm like, oh, let's
go get Mexican food.

00:02:41.873 --> 00:02:42.740
And he's like, nope.

00:02:42.740 --> 00:02:44.775
So basically I would get a
driverless car that would say

00:02:44.775 --> 00:02:46.025
like, where do you want to go?

00:02:46.025 --> 00:02:47.626
And I'm not going
to take you there.

00:02:47.626 --> 00:02:49.250
I'm going to make
you feel comfortable.

00:02:49.250 --> 00:02:52.547
So I would say, first
off-- actually it's

00:02:52.547 --> 00:02:55.300
not first, because I've
already been talking.

00:02:55.300 --> 00:02:58.730
First off, I did not take
my ADD medicine today.

00:02:58.730 --> 00:03:06.154
Probably pretty obvious, but
I'm going to try and focus.

00:03:06.154 --> 00:03:10.866
I did take my anxiety medicine,
but taking my anxiety medicine

00:03:10.866 --> 00:03:14.275
without taking my ADD medicine
makes me a little bit sleepy.

00:03:14.275 --> 00:03:16.400
And then it's rainy, which
makes me totally sleepy.

00:03:16.400 --> 00:03:20.020
I don't know how you
guys are awake ever.

00:03:20.020 --> 00:03:22.760
And also the entire time
I'm like, look, rain!

00:03:22.760 --> 00:03:23.690
Rain!

00:03:23.690 --> 00:03:25.195
Because in Texas
we don't get this.

00:03:25.195 --> 00:03:27.070
And everybody else is
like, ah, fucking rain.

00:03:29.830 --> 00:03:32.125
So first of all,
good job on the rain,

00:03:32.125 --> 00:03:35.040
and also good job on
seasons, having seasons.

00:03:35.040 --> 00:03:36.040
That's a great thing.

00:03:36.040 --> 00:03:38.540
We don't have that in Texas.

00:03:38.540 --> 00:03:46.210
I am going to do a reading,
and this is literally

00:03:46.210 --> 00:03:47.490
a page and half.

00:03:47.490 --> 00:03:49.181
But that way you
can say, oh yeah,

00:03:49.181 --> 00:03:52.870
I've been to a Jenny
Lawson reading.

00:03:52.870 --> 00:03:54.329
I'm stepping on a
lot of wires here

00:03:54.329 --> 00:03:55.536
and I might get electrocuted.

00:03:55.536 --> 00:03:56.675
I'm sure it will be fine.

00:03:56.675 --> 00:03:57.610
It'll be OK.

00:04:00.370 --> 00:04:08.527
So I'm going to--
let's see-- I'm

00:04:08.527 --> 00:04:10.652
going to skip that one,
which is a little bit dark.

00:04:10.652 --> 00:04:16.190
Let's do this one, which
is-- and I will preface this

00:04:16.190 --> 00:04:19.526
by saying, just in case
you have no idea who I am,

00:04:19.526 --> 00:04:20.492
that's totally OK.

00:04:20.492 --> 00:04:28.500
I am weird and slightly--
more than slightly-- off,

00:04:28.500 --> 00:04:31.050
and I write weird
things on the internet,

00:04:31.050 --> 00:04:33.950
and sometimes in books.

00:04:33.950 --> 00:04:36.775
And weirdly enough,
people actually like them.

00:04:36.775 --> 00:04:41.370
And I actually just found
out that this strange book

00:04:41.370 --> 00:04:43.790
is on the "New York Time"'s
list for the seventh week

00:04:43.790 --> 00:04:45.956
in a row, which is very
weird because you look at it

00:04:45.956 --> 00:04:50.845
and it's like, Mindy Kaling
and that asshole O'Reilly.

00:04:53.510 --> 00:04:55.071
And it's all these
people that you're

00:04:55.071 --> 00:04:56.279
like, oh, I know that person.

00:04:56.279 --> 00:04:57.080
I know that person.

00:04:57.080 --> 00:04:58.500
I hate that person.

00:04:58.500 --> 00:05:02.027
And then there's a dead
raccoon, so that's-- actually

00:05:02.027 --> 00:05:02.860
that's kind of nice.

00:05:02.860 --> 00:05:08.930
So "I Found a Kindred Soul, and
He Has a Very Healthy Coat."

00:05:08.930 --> 00:05:11.589
A few weeks ago, I was at the
pharmacy picking up my meds,

00:05:11.589 --> 00:05:13.505
and I'm starting into
the drive through window

00:05:13.505 --> 00:05:15.800
and thinking about how awesome
it is to live in a world

00:05:15.800 --> 00:05:18.150
where you can pick up
drugs in a drive through.

00:05:18.150 --> 00:05:20.641
And that's when I noticed
something strange next

00:05:20.641 --> 00:05:21.849
to the pharmacist's register.

00:05:21.849 --> 00:05:23.723
And I don't know if you
can see this picture,

00:05:23.723 --> 00:05:29.600
but this is an open box
of milk bone dog biscuits.

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:32.460
And I thought, well that's odd.

00:05:32.460 --> 00:05:34.485
But maybe someone
returned them because they

00:05:34.485 --> 00:05:36.868
were stale or
something, and then I

00:05:36.868 --> 00:05:39.150
thought it was even odder
that someone would realize

00:05:39.150 --> 00:05:42.120
the dog biscuits had gone
stale, because dogs usually

00:05:42.120 --> 00:05:43.860
aren't very good at
not eating cookies

00:05:43.860 --> 00:05:45.797
even if they're fairly shitty.

00:05:45.797 --> 00:05:47.785
I mean, dogs eat used
diapers if you let them,

00:05:47.785 --> 00:05:49.134
so I'm pretty sure
none of them are

00:05:49.134 --> 00:05:51.761
saying no to eating cookies, but
then the pharmacist came back.

00:05:51.761 --> 00:05:54.494
And while he was
ringing me up he

00:05:54.494 --> 00:05:57.740
reached over and picked up a
handful of broken dog biscuits

00:05:57.740 --> 00:06:01.090
and ate them.

00:06:01.090 --> 00:06:04.832
I thought, wait.

00:06:04.832 --> 00:06:07.290
Am I high right now?

00:06:07.290 --> 00:06:08.620
Is he high?

00:06:08.620 --> 00:06:09.760
Am I being tested?

00:06:09.760 --> 00:06:11.155
Should I say something?

00:06:11.155 --> 00:06:13.502
But I didn't, because I'm
pretty sure that you're not

00:06:13.502 --> 00:06:14.880
supposed to accuse
the man giving you

00:06:14.880 --> 00:06:15.730
drugs of eating dog food.

00:06:15.730 --> 00:06:17.980
And then I signed for the
drugs and then I drove away.

00:06:17.980 --> 00:06:19.740
And I thought to
myself, is it possible

00:06:19.740 --> 00:06:22.440
that he accidentally
ate the dog biscuits?

00:06:22.440 --> 00:06:25.108
Or maybe someone is always
stealing his food at work

00:06:25.108 --> 00:06:28.242
so he decided to put his
tasty human cookies, maybe

00:06:28.242 --> 00:06:31.360
for humans, not out of
humans, into a [INAUDIBLE] box

00:06:31.360 --> 00:06:32.710
to keep them safe.

00:06:32.710 --> 00:06:35.070
Or maybe he just likes
to entertain himself

00:06:35.070 --> 00:06:37.970
by seeing if people will
stop him and say, dude,

00:06:37.970 --> 00:06:39.837
you're eating dog food.

00:06:39.837 --> 00:06:42.752
Those would be good
people probably.

00:06:42.752 --> 00:06:44.647
I'm not one of those people.

00:06:44.647 --> 00:06:47.230
But then I spent the whole day
thinking, why the dog biscuits?

00:06:47.230 --> 00:06:49.688
So I went back today to ask,
but the dog biscuits were gone

00:06:49.688 --> 00:06:51.844
and the dog biscuit
eating guy was also gone.

00:06:51.844 --> 00:06:53.510
And I thought, can I
ask this pharmacist

00:06:53.510 --> 00:06:55.365
if the other pharmacist
who eats dog food

00:06:55.365 --> 00:06:57.490
is around because I really
need to know this story?

00:06:57.490 --> 00:06:58.680
And the answer is no.

00:06:58.680 --> 00:06:59.990
No, I can't.

00:06:59.990 --> 00:07:02.676
But I still really want
to know because I suspect

00:07:02.676 --> 00:07:04.582
that I would be great
friends with this guy,

00:07:04.582 --> 00:07:07.484
because anyone who would hide
crackers in a dog food box

00:07:07.484 --> 00:07:09.890
seems like someone I'd
want to hang out with.

00:07:09.890 --> 00:07:11.906
Although someone who
eats dog food for fun

00:07:11.906 --> 00:07:14.100
seems slightly
more questionable.

00:07:14.100 --> 00:07:17.130
Except now I'm wondering if
maybe milk bones are really

00:07:17.130 --> 00:07:19.300
delicious, and he's just
a genius who discovered

00:07:19.300 --> 00:07:20.539
really cheap cookies.

00:07:20.539 --> 00:07:22.663
Cookies you don't have to
tell your judgemental vet

00:07:22.663 --> 00:07:25.880
about when your dog gets in the
pantry and eats all of them.

00:07:25.880 --> 00:07:27.690
You did still have to
call the vet, though,

00:07:27.690 --> 00:07:30.825
when your cat has eaten a toy,
which consists of a tinkle bell

00:07:30.825 --> 00:07:33.329
and feather and a poof ball,
all tied together with twine.

00:07:33.329 --> 00:07:34.870
This is actually
happened to me once,

00:07:34.870 --> 00:07:36.952
and it was the worst
because the vet told me

00:07:36.952 --> 00:07:38.660
I would have to ply
my cat with laxatives

00:07:38.660 --> 00:07:41.730
in order to make the
toy pass through easily.

00:07:41.730 --> 00:07:43.356
And then inspect his
poop to make sure

00:07:43.356 --> 00:07:45.780
that the toy had passed,
because otherwise they would

00:07:45.780 --> 00:07:47.120
have to do open cat surgery.

00:07:47.120 --> 00:07:49.090
And then it finally
did start to pass,

00:07:49.090 --> 00:07:51.000
but just the first part
with the tinkle bell.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:53.291
And the cat's freaking out,
because he was running away

00:07:53.291 --> 00:07:57.074
from the tinkle bell, which was
hanging out of his butthole.

00:07:57.074 --> 00:08:00.395
And I called the vet, and he
said to definitely not pull

00:08:00.395 --> 00:08:01.936
on the twine, because
it can pull out

00:08:01.936 --> 00:08:05.210
his intestines, which would
be the grossest pinata ever.

00:08:05.210 --> 00:08:08.277
And so instead, I just ran up
to the cat with some scissors

00:08:08.277 --> 00:08:10.610
to cut off the tinkle bell,
which impressively was still

00:08:10.610 --> 00:08:13.502
tinkling after seeing the
things no tinkle should ever

00:08:13.502 --> 00:08:14.235
have to see.

00:08:14.235 --> 00:08:16.110
And I think probably
the cat was running away

00:08:16.110 --> 00:08:17.780
both because of the
tinkle bell and also

00:08:17.780 --> 00:08:19.540
because I was chasing
it with scissors,

00:08:19.540 --> 00:08:23.790
screaming let me help you.

00:08:23.790 --> 00:08:26.560
If I was good friends with that
dog food eating pharmacist,

00:08:26.560 --> 00:08:29.245
I would have called him to tell
him all about the tinkle bell

00:08:29.245 --> 00:08:31.420
issue, because I think he
would have appreciated it.

00:08:31.420 --> 00:08:33.154
But I never found
him again, because I

00:08:33.154 --> 00:08:35.612
was worried that if I ever
asked to see the dog food eating

00:08:35.612 --> 00:08:39.240
pharmacist, the other pharmacist
would stop giving me drugs.

00:08:39.240 --> 00:08:41.200
This all feels a
bit discriminatory,

00:08:41.200 --> 00:08:46.110
but I can't explain exactly why.

00:08:46.110 --> 00:08:49.112
[APPLAUSE]

00:08:51.214 --> 00:08:52.130
Shortest reading ever.

00:08:56.875 --> 00:09:01.554
So I've heard that this is
